<dl id="n41187b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41187b">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41187b"> 187(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> joyful out of his / eyes <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n41187b"><li>FW 240.32f. </li><li><a href="../../flex/kd/lexkd.htm#n41187b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kd/l39kd.htm#n41187b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n41187b">MS BL 47477-42</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:092 <a name="kdd0" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kdd0">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kd/kdd0.htm#n41187b">Draft: II.1&sect;4.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"> <font color="green">[<font size="-1">PERSONAL CHARACTERISTICS</font>]</font> On his taking leave of Cuno in 1769, the conversation turned upon the improbability of their meeting again. Swedenborg spoke with eager anticipation of the last great change which he knew must come to him before long; and, as he spoke, &ldquo;he looked so innocent and so <mark>joyful out of his eyes</mark>, as I had never seen him look before.&rdquo; <small> George Trobridge, <a name="GTLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#GTLS"><cite title="source">A Life of Emanuel Swedenborg</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (??) 299 [305]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
